{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558856/1945081701/0551.xml":{"full_text":"Weekly Card\nParly Is Held\nAt Wricrhlsville\nThe Carolina Yacht club enter\ntained Wednesday morning at the\nweekly bridge luncheon for mem\nbers and their guests. Bridge was\nin play at 15 tables during the\nmorning followed by luncheon al\n1:30 o'clock. Hostesses for the day\nwere Mrs. Fred Burr and Mrs. Eu\ngene Hicks. High scorer of the\ngame was Mrs. John A. Elmore\nwhile low scorer was Mrs. O. L\nBrowne.\nHostesses for next Wednesday\nwill be Mrs. B. R. Morrison and\nMrs. Alice Andrews.\nAmong those attending were:\nMrs. Lynn B. Tillery, Mrs. W. S.\nBaker, Mrs. Robert W. Marye, Miss\nLois Toomer, Mrs. Walker Taylor,\nMrs. Oscar Peck, Mrs. William\nEmerson, Mrs. David H. Scott,\nMrs. W. L. Beery, Mrs. Frank Park\nof Greenville, Mrs. John A. El\nmore, Mrs. R. J. Griffith of At\nlanta, Ga.. Mrs. George Thomas,\nMrs. Horace Emerson, Mrs. George\nClark, Mrs. Hazel Powell of Lum\nberton\nMrs. I. J. Sutton, Mrs. O. L.\nBrowne, Mrs. Horace Pearsall,\nMrs. Fred Pearsall, Mrs. Van\nToomer, Mrs. C. Wayne Spencer.\nMrs. John Ryssey, Mrs. Robert\nMurphy, Mrs. T. K. Lynch, Mrs.\nT. D. Love, Jr., Mrs. C. M. Wade,\nMrs. Emsley A. Laney, Mrs. Joseph\nW. Hooper, Mrs. Milton Best of\nFremont, Mrs. Wright Dixon, Mrs.\nduBrutz Poisson, Mrs. Almeda S.\nEdwards, Mrs. W. B. Taylor, Miss\nVirginia Herrin, Miss Jane Wil\nliams, Mrs. Richard C. Meyer;\nMrs. John Whitaker, Miss Ellen\nWhitehead, Mrs. J. E. Evans, Miss\nJane Beatty, Mrs. F. K. McKoy,\nMrs. H. C. Kietz, Mrs. Lowell\nWhite, Mrs. Edwin B. Josey, Mrs.\nE. H. Munson, Mrs. W. G. White\nhead, Mrs. Claude Howell, Mrs. J.\nBuren Sidbury, Mrs. James E.\nJohnson of Lumberton, Mrs. Waiter\nCurtis, Mrs. W. F Brown of Lex\nington, Mrs. Heide Trask, Mrs. F.\nW. Brown. Mrs. R. G. Hodgkin and\nMrs. James A. Brown.\n\nBIRTH ANNOUNCED\nLieut, and Mrs. Robert F. Bel\nlomy announce the birth of a\ndaughter, Barbara Lynn, on Aug\nust 13, at Mary Washington hospi\ntal, Fredericksburg, Va. Mrs. Bel\nlomy is the former Miss Marie\nSaleem of Wilmington.\n\nBUY VICTORY BONDS!\nFoot Comfort!\nIN YOUR DAINTIEST SHOES\nPERSONALS\nMrs, Ida Evans has returned to\nher home in Warrenton, Va., after\nspending the past ten days as the\nhouseguest of Miss Jennie Murchi\nson and Mrs. Asheiy Curt s at then\nhome on Wrightsviiie Beach.\n\nDr. and Mrs. Thorne Sparkman\nreturned to their home in Chatta\nnooga, Tenn., Thursday morning\nby rrtotor a.ter spending the past\ntwo weeks at the George B. Elliott\ncottage on South Lumina avenue,\nWrightsviiie E>each,\n\nMrs. Charles M. Stewart and\nthree sons of Baltimore, Md., are\noccupying the Van Leuven cottage\non West Oxford street at Wrights\nviiie Beach for the month of Au\ngust.\n\nMr. and Mrs. Robert W. Baker\nof Greensboro, will arrive Monday\nto occupy the George B. Elliott\ncottage at Wrightsviiie Beach,\nwhich they have recently pur\nchased. Mr. Baker is president\nand owner of the Bluebell Overall\nfactory in Greensboro. Both Mr.\nand Mrs, Baker and family are\npleasantly remember here hav\ning spent a number of seasons at\nWrightsviiie Beach.\n\nMr. and Mrs. Robert M. Williams\nhave as their guest at their apart\nment at Wrightsviiie Beach Mrs.\nWilliam Parsley of Charlotte.\n\nMiss Madelhe deRossett of New\nYork city, who is on the staff ol\nHarper's Bazaar, is the guest A\nMiss Jennie Murchison and Mrs.\nAsheiy Curtis at Wrightsviiie\nBeach.\n\nMrs. Robert Gwaltney, who has\nbeen spending a month at the\nBeachland cottage at Wrightsviiie\nBeach, and visiting Mrs. Francis\nCurtzwiler, has returned to h e r\nhome in Short Hills, N. J.\n\nA. Glenn Holt of Burlington, ar\nrived last evening to spend the\nweek-end with his family at their\ncottage on North Lumina Avenue,\nWrightsviiie Beach.\n\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Lomax and\nchildren of Charlotte, formerly ol\nHarbor Island, are spending their\nvacation at Wrightsviiie Beach.\n\nCol. Royce S. McClelland arriv\ned from Washington, D. C., Tues\nday even ng to spend a five-day\nleave with Mrs. McClelland at\ntheir Wrightsviiie Beach cottage.\nHe will return on Sunday to Wash\nington, where he is stationed as the\nlaw member on the secretary of\nwar's disability review board. Mrs.\nMcClelland will remain *at her\nWrightsviiie Beach cottage for\nseveral weeks longer.\n\nMrs. Edward Carpenter of New\nBrunswick, N. J., is the guest of\nMrs. Ashley Curtis and Miss Jen\nI Turn To Page 5 For 1\nNATHAN\u2019S I\nAUGUST I\nCLEARANCE SALE!\nGill's Hotel Special\nCoffee and Chicory\nhas the extra strength\nneeded to make iced\ncoffee extra delicious.\nQ ILL'S HOTEL SPECIAL\n\u25a0UiMiifiivnn-1\nCAMPUS COLORS\nAP Newsfeatures\nBACK-TO-SCHOOL calls for the\nright lipstick too. A new winged\nvictory shade is on the beam for\nyoung girls.\nMiss Ualewood\nOf Madison, Weds\nLt. E. B. Register\n1\nMr. and Mrs. John Hardy Gate\nwood of Madison, announce the\nmarriage*of their daughter, Mildred\nWinters, to 1st. Lieut. Edward B.\nRegister, Jr., United States Army\nAir Corps, son of Mrs. .and Mrs.\nEdward B. Register of Wilmington.\nThe marriage took place at Con\nway, S. C., on August 8.__\nFor her marriage the bride wore\na street length navy blue sheer\ndress with matching accessories.\nHer shoulder corsage was of red\nroses. She is a graduate of Madi\nson High school class of 1945.\nnie Murchison at their summer\nhome on South Lumina avenue,\nWrightsville B*each.\n\nMr. and Mrs. George Coble and\ntwo children of Lexington, are va\ncationing at the Ocean Terrace at\nWrightsville Beach.\n\nMrs. U. L. Spence, Jr., is spend\ning several days in Carthage with\nrelatives. She expects to return to\nthe city the first of next wreek.\n\nMiss Olive Wadsworth, of New\nOrleans, La., niece of John N.\nAlexius, is visiting her uncle and\naunt at their summer home on\nHarbor Island. Mrs. William Em\nerson, who has been residing in\nNew Orleans, accompanied Miss\nWadsworth home for a stay with\nh parents.\n\nMrs. Emmett Crow, Jr., of Hous\nton, Texas, who has been visiting\nher sister in Boston, returned tr.\nWilm'ngton Thursday for a visit\nw'ith Mr. and Mrs. Emmett Crow\non Masonboro Sound, she will be\njoined here shortly by' her hus\nband.\nThe Jewel Bex GIFT SHOP\nI Wiiminf ton's Only Downstair*\nStore Headquarters Pot\nFINE GIFTS\nCome In and Make Your\nSelections!\nLocated Downstairs\nTHE JEWEL BOX\n109 North Frcnt St.\nmmmmmmmmr\namt\nAMERICA\u2019S WASH WORD Ijj\nAIDS HEALING\nHELPS NEW SKIN FORM\nSoothes and Protect* Minor Burns,\nDiaper Hash, Chafing, Abrasions,\nScratches, Simple Cuts\u2014Wounds.\nget This Pare White Petrolcem Jelly\nVictory Menus\nBy CHARLOTTE ADAMS\n>e Family Will Love Waffles for\nSaturday Night Supper\nTomato Juice Cocktail\nr/affles with Cream Dried Beef\nCucumber and Lettuce Salad\nBaked Bananas\n(Recipes serve four)\nA'aifles With Creamed Dried Beef\n2 cups sifted flour.\n3 teaspoons baking powder.\n1-2 teaspoon salt.\n3 eggs.\n1 1-2 cups fnilk.\n1-4 cup melted shortening.\nMix and sift flour, baking pow\nder and salt. Combine egg yolks\nand milk and add to the dry mix\nture. And melted shortening (not\ntoo hot) an fold in stiffly beaten\negg whites. Bake-in a hot waffl;\niron. Serve with:\nCream Dried-Beef\n1 package dried beef.\nDash of pepper.\n1-2 teaspoon onion juice.\n3 cups milk.\n1-4 cup butter or margarine.\n3-4 cup flour.\nIf you do not care for the salti\nness of dried beef, cover it with\nboiling water for a few minutes\nand then drain. Otherwise, add it\nto the cream sauce, shredded and\ndry. Make the cream sauce by\nblending melted butter or magaine\nand ou. Then add seasonings,\nonion juice and milk and cook\nover boiling water until thick, stir\nring constantly. Then add dried\nbeef and hold over hot water for\n10 minutes, stirring occasionally.\nWOMEN\u2019S SERVICES\nSTOP RECRUITING\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 16.\u2014(\u00a3>)\u2014\nThe Women's services in the armed\nforces have halted recruiting and\nwith the exception of the WACs,\nare not accepting any more enlist\nments.\nThe Woman\u2019s Army Corps, al\nthough not making any drive for\nmore women, still will take women\nwho want to enlist.\nThe Coast Guard\u2019s Spars and the\nNavy s Waves and the Marine wom\nen Marines, however, have closed\ntheir books for enlistments.\nAll four services are turning to\nthe task of demobilization with the\nWACs and women Marines using\nthe Army point score system for\ndischarges and the SPARS and\nWAVEs using the Navy\u2019s.\nThe WACs \u201ccritical\u201d score for\ndischarge is 44 points, based on\none point for each month\u2019s service\nand an additional point for each\nmonth\u2019s overseas duty, five points\neach for medals and campaign\nservice stars, 5 and 12 points for\neach child up to a maximum of\nthree.\nThe Marine score computed upon\nthe same basis is 25.\nThe Spars and Waves have set\na score of 29 for enlisted personnel\nand 35 for officers.\nTO SELL TIRES\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 16.\u2014(A>)\nAirplane tires and tubes declared\nsurplus by the Army and Navy\nwill be sold for civilian use through\nthe Commerce Department's of\nfice of surplus property, it was\nannounced today.\nWheels made of laminated wood\nwere tried out in London subways\nto lessen noise and reduce weight.\nThe bridegroom, a graduate oi\nNew Hanover High school in Wil\nmington, was employed by the At\nlantic Coast Line railroad pr.or to\nentering service in 1942. He re\nceived his pilot wings at Marfa\nField, Texas, and served eight\nmonths in the European War Thea\ntre. He was awarded the Distin\nguished Flying Cross and Air Med\nal with three Oak Leaf clusters.\nLieut. Register is an instructor at\nMcDill Field.\nGLASSES REPAIRED\nLENSES REPLACED\n3In Dpt cal Shop I\n105 N. FRONT ST.\nIn Peoples Bank Bldg.\nja!i\nMOSQUITOES\nwith\nFLY-TOX\nKills Flies and\nMany Other Insects\n_ AT DEALERS EVERYWHERE\n\nSAIT SO/ME 1\nAWAy -JGI\n'OR THRIfT AND VARIETY IN WINTER MEALS j\n^^^CannmtjSfitMl^tOW-atyw^meS^^^j al\nSupper Party\nHeld At Club\nAmong those attending the regu\nlar Thursday evening buffet sup\nper party at the Surf club on\nWrightsville Beach were the fol\nlowing members and their guests:\nMr. and Mrs. E. L. White, Mr\nand Mrs. George Coble of Lexing\nton, Mr. and Mrs. Emmett Crow\nand guests, Mr. and Mrs. L. P/il\nCampbell, Mrs. A. K. Cooper, i\\.,\nMr. and Mrs. John N. Alexius\nMiss Louise Davis of Norfolk, Va..\nMrs. William Emerson, Miss Olive\nWadsworth, of New Orleans, La.,\nMr. and Mrs. Willard Cantwell,\nDr. and Mrs. B. R. Morrison and\nguests, Mr. and Mrs. J. A. El\nmore, Mr. and Mrs. G. A. Card\nwell, Jr., Mrs. Guy A. Cardwell,\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Roe, Miss\nLaura Roe, Pfc. Walter McCor\nmick, Miss Elizabeth Hardwicke,\nMrs. Mary Nixon Hardwicke,\nMrs. Thomas F. Darden, Miss De\nlores Chfatham, Mrs. Jackson\nBalch, Mrs. Joseph Dunn, Mrs. B.\nP. Eggleston, Jr., Miss Louise\nWells, Miss Betty Henderson, Miss\nElizabeth Bridgers, S-Sgt. Pres\nton Alexander, D. S. Avenger and\nparty;\nMr. and Mrs. Louis B. Orrell,\nMrs. A. Sidney Williams, Miss\nMarguerite Walker, Dr. and Mrs.\nJoseph W. Hooper, Col. and Mrs\nRoyee S. McClelland of Washing\nton. D. C., Mrs Charles S. Parker\nof New York city, Thomas Orrell,\nMrs. Charles Becker, Mr. and\nMrs. Tom Davis, Paul Wilson, Mr.\nand Mrs. Lester W* Preston, Mr.\nand Mrs. Rinaldo B. Page, Mrs.\nJames L. King of Columbus, Ga.,\nMr. and Mrs. J. Douglas Taylor,\nMr. and Mrs. A. Glenn Holt, Dr.\nand Mrs. William Dosher, Mr.\nand Mrs. W. C. Park, Mr. and\nW. T. Cheatham and guests, Mr.\nMrs. P. F. Halsey, Mr. and Mrs.\nand Mrs. Leslie Marbury and\nguests, Dr. and Mrs. David Mur\nchison and guests, Mrs. Marsden\nBellamy, Jr., and guests, Mrs.\nMichael Brown and guests, Mr. and\nMrs. George Stearns and guest,\nMrs. Francis Curtzwiler and\nguests, Mrs. J. Irving Corbett\nand guests, Mrs. John C. Wessell,\nJr., and guests, Mr. and Mrs.\nRaymond H.\\ Holland and guests,\nMr. and Mrs. W. A. Raney and\nguests.\nFun To Embroider\n7029\nby Alice Brooks,\nViolets in true-to-life colors look\nreal enough to pluck, done in\neasy embroidery stitches on your\nlinens. It\u2019s stitchery that\u2019s fas\ncinating.\nViolets in easy stitchery in their\nown colors make linens you\u2019ll love.\nPattern 7029 has a\u00ab transfer of 8\nmotifs 2 1-2x4 to 4x12 4-3 in.\nSend FIFTEEN CENTS in coins\nfor this pattern to Wilmington\nStar-News Household Arts Dept.,\n259 W. 14th St., New York 11,\nN. Y. Print plainly NAME, AD\nDRESS and PATTERN NUMBER.\nJust out! Send fifteen cents more\nfor our NEW 1945 Needlwork Book\n\u201494 illustrations of designs: cro\ncheting, knitting, embroidery, dolls\nather toys, home decoration. Free\nPattern for two crocheted hand\noags printed right in the book.\nMan Plunges From Top\nOf Empire State Roof\nNEW YORK, Aug. 16.\u2014HR\u2014 An\nmidentified man climbed over the\naarapet on the 86th floor observa\n;ory of the 102-story Emp: State\nauilding today and plunged to his\nleath into 33rd street near Fifth\nivenue.\nSeveral thousand persons, observ\nng the second day peace holiday,\nvere in the vie nity when the man's\nlody came hurtling down.\nPolice said the leap of 1,000 feet\nvas the longest on record in New\nfork. Other persons have jumped\nrom higher levels, police said, but\nlave landed on set-backs.\nThe victim had no papers or\nnarks of identification.\n__\nWATCH YOUR STEP\nDuring 1943, 94,500 persons\nvere killed in accidents in* the\nInited States. Approximately 9,\n00,000 injuries were sustained,\nvhile 320,000 cases resulting in\nome permanent disability, such\ns an amputated finger, stiffened\noint, or blindness.\nWhile the most common danger\nan automobile is from lack of\nibrication, there is such a thing\ns overdoing it. It is important\nat only to use the right kind of I\nibricant, but also the right Ij\nnount.\u2014General Motors User\u2019s D\nuide. I!\nCOLLEGE CREDITS\nAP Newsfeatures\nREQUIRED equipment\nPerennial classic shirt in beig<\nor blue checked rayon flannel, de\nsigned by Korday for wear witl\njeans or skirts\u2014and washable.\nWomen Of The Moose\nWill Sponsor Party\nThe Women of the Moose wil\nsponsor a bingo party on Frida}\nevening at 8 o\u2019clock at the Moose\nLodge, 416 .North .Front .street\nThe public is invited to attend.\n\nMilitary Cut-Backs\nSolve Nation\u2019s Coal,\nRailroad Problems\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 16.\u2014 W\nArmy officials said today tha*\nmilitary cut-backs have solved th<\nnation\u2019s coal shortage and railroac\nfreight transportation problems.\nAt a news conference, Lt. G<h\nBrehon Somervell, chief of the\nArmy\u2019s Service Forces, and othei\nofficials stated that the cut-bach\nin Army coal contracts would\nsave 145,000,000 tons in the nex1\n12 months.\nThis reduction, they said, fol\nlowed a saving of more than 20,\n000,000 tons in cancelled contracts\nafter V-E Day.\nThe present national coal deficii\nhas been estimated at 25,000,000\ntons, the Army spokesmen said,\nand hence these new cuts will make\nmore than 120,000,000 tons avail\nable for reconversion and civilian\nuse.\nTremendous cuts in supplies,\nthey added, will ease the freighl\nsituation so much that the conges\ntion now resent will soon cease\nto exist.\nBUY VICTORY BONDS!\nMAKE\nICE CREAM]\nAt home\u2014Any flavor \u2014Delicious \u2014Smooth\nNo ice crystals \u2014No cooking \u2014No re\nwhipping\u2014No scorched flavor \u2014Easy\nInexpensive \u201420 recipes in each 15< pkg.\nPlease send this ad for free full-size sam\nple offer, or buy from your grocer.\nLOtlDOtlOCRRy\nBrand Homemade Ice Cream\nSTABILIZER\nX. X X \\Jk XmX y-JX-A H\nKiwanis Club Announces I\nFar-Reaching Program I\nSeeking to speed reconversion\nand aid returning veterans, Ki\nwanis International today announc\ned nine far-reaching post-war ob\njectives as the Kiwanis club of\nWilmington considered ways and\nmeans of rendering greater com\nmunity service in peacetime.\nIn a special message to 2,300\nclubs throughout the United States\nand Canada, Hamilton Holt, Ma\ncon, Ga., president of Kiwanis\nInternational, declaied that 149,\n000 Kiwanians \u201cwill not shrink\nfrom the problems of reconversion\nthat lie ahead.\u2019\u2019\nI Holt told President Truman and\nPrime Minister King of Canada\nin telegrams read to the local club\nthat Kiwanis International would\nlend its wholehearted cooperation\nin meeting and solving the prob\nlems of post-war reconstruction.\n\u201cSince Dunkirk and Pearl Har\nbor,\u201d he said, \u201cKiwanis manpower\nhas been marshalled behind the\nallied war effort. These resources\nnow will be directed toward the\nbuilding of peace, unity and op\nportunity.\u201d\nEmory H. Southerland, presi\ndent of the Kiwanis club of Wil\nmington, said that Kiwanis In\nternational\u2019s post-war objectives\nhad the unanimous endorsement\nof Kiwanians here. He revealed\nthat the service organization\u2019s\ntheme would be \u201cBuild for Peace\nUnity\u2014Opportunity.\nThe nine objectives follow:\n1. Develop an understanding of\nthe United Nations Charter in\nsupport of wofld peace.\n2. Aid returning veterans.\n3. Encourage sound programs\nof reconversion.\n4. Strengthen democracy by per\nsonal acceptance of citizenship re\nsponsibilities.\n5. Expand youth services to build\ncharacter and citizenship.\n6. Mobilize public opinion in sup\nport of individual enterprise and\nopportunity.\n7. Conserve -natural resource*.\n8. Further good will between\nCanada and the United States as a*\noutstanding example of intern*\ntional cooperation.\n9. Develop national unity througl\nincreased emphasis on human an*\nspiritual values.\nRural Officer, ATU Men\nNap Alleged \u201cShinciV1\nBrunswick county rural police\nman O. W. Perry and A. T. U\nagents Gray and Smithwick ar\nrested James Sam Brown and Bic\u00ab\nMuncy Wednesday, while the paii\nwere allegedly operating a 15(\ngallon submarine still in the Mid\nway section of Brunswick county\nOfficer Perry reported that eigh\nbarrels of mash and 20 gallon* o:\nnon-tax-paid whiskey were da\nstroyed.\nBrown and Muncy were placed\nunder $500 bond each and bounc\nover to the October term of Fed\neral court by the U. S. Commis\nsioner after a hearing.\nNow, with limited driving, it is\nbest to have a car lubricated\nevery two months, even though it\nmay have been driven only a few\nhundred miles since the last lubri\ncation.\u2014General Motor* User'*\nGuide.\nFor Foot That Sweat\nWith Missive Odor\nEmerald OH Mast Give Cemplete\nSatiate often or Money Seek\nDon\u2019t wait another day. You can re\nmote the disagreeable odors quickly with\na few drops of this powerful penetrating\n.Antiseptic Oil.\nDruggists everywhere who know, say that\nEmeranl Oil is the speediest and most ef\nfective preparation they have ever handled\nfor acting, perspiring, ill-smelling feet.\nThe very minute that thia wonderful\nfoot balm touches these sore, tender, ach\ning feet, you will get relief. It\u2019s simply\natnasirg how quickly it acts, and no mat\nter wh t others may tell you, there\u2019s\nnothing just as good.\nFUTRELLE S PHARMACY\nRelieves it Quickly\nWhen you have a bad night and\nWake the next morning feeling\nfoggy, jittery and generally \u201call-in\u201d\nlet \u201cBC\u201d lend a helping-hand. \u201cBC'1\noffers extra-fast relief because its\ningredients are readily assimilated.\nAlso relieves neuralgia and muscu\nlar aches. 10c and 25c sizes. Use only\nas directed. Consult a physician\nwhen pains persist\nAs seen in Me Call\u2019s\u2019*'\nand \"Seventeen**\ns3-5\u00ab to *3\nStyled for young modems... f eorlher\nlight... fashion-right... of fine sturdy\nbrown or black gabardine or spark\nling black imitation patent with\nwear-tested plastic solos.\nSu-Anii Shoe Store j\nI footwear for Clil\nf 109^2 NORTH FRONT STREET","height":"27172","width":"20480"}}
